To create an automatically generated table of contents in a LATEX document, you can use the `tocbasic` environment provided by the KOMA-script bundle. First, you need to load this bundle and the `fancyhdr` package to style the header and the table of contents. Then, you can use the `tocbasic` environment to define the table of contents structure and generate it automatically. Let's assume you have a document named `mydocument.tex` with the following content:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{koma-script}
\usepackage{fancyhdr}

\addtokomafont{tableofcontents}{\bfseries}
\addtokomafont{toc}{\bfseries}

\begin{document}
\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
\lipsum[1-5]

\section{First Section}
\lipsum[1-5]

\section{Second Section}
\lipsum[1-5]

\section{Conclusion}
\lipsum[1-5]

\listoffigures
\listoftables

\ref{label1}
\ref{label2}
\ref{label3}
\ref{label4}
\ref{label5}

\end{document}
```
To include the automatic table of contents, you need to add the following lines in the preamble:
```latex
\usepackage{tocbasic}
\makeatletter
\let\TcOfContents\tableofcontents
\let\TcEntry\tableoftitle

\renewcommand\listfigures{%
  \renewcommand\contentslineformat{simple}{\figurename~\thecontentslabel}%
  \addtocontents{lof}{\protect\addvspace{10pt}}%
  \listoffigures
}

\renewcommand\listoftables{%
  \renewcommand\contentslineformat{simple}{Table~\thecontentslabel}%
  \addtocontents{lot}{\protect\addvspace{10pt}}%
  \listoftables
}

\makeatother
```
Now, the table of contents will be generated automatically when you run LaTeX. Note that you might need to adjust the layout of the table of contents to suit your specific needs. You can do this by customizing the `tocbasic` options, like the font size, style, etc.

To create a chessboard diagram in LaTeX using the FEN notation, you'll need to use the tikzpackage. Here's a code snippet that demonstrates how to create such a diagram using the tikzlibrary and the fenenumbers package. Make sure to compile the code with XeLaTeX or LuaLaTeX, as they provide better support for math and graphical content:
```latex
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{positioning}
\usepackage{fennumbers}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[
    >=stealth',
    shorten >=1pt,
    shorten <=1pt,
    node distance = 2mm,
    on grid,
    piace/.style = {%
        fill = #1,
        draw = #1,
        circle,
        inner sep = 1.5pt,
        minimum width = 2em,
        text depth = 1pt
    },
    piace/.default = white
]

\coordinate(board-1,1);
\coordinate(board-8,1);
\coordinate(board-1,8);
\coordinate(board-8,8);
\coordinate(board-8,1);
\coordinate(board-1,8);
\coordinate(board-1,1);
\coordinate(board-8,8);
\coordinate(board-8,1);
\coordinate(board-8,8);
\coordinate(current,1);
\coordinate(target,8);

\draw[line width=10pt, Piace-White] (current.west) to [out=135, in=45] (target.east);
\draw[line width=10pt, Piace-White] (current.south) to [out=135, in=45] (target.north);

\node[above] at (current.north) {1};
\node[above] at (current.west) {8};
\node[below] at (current.south) {1};
\node[below] at (current.east) {8};

\foreach \pos in {(1,1), (1,8), (8,1), (8,8), (8,1), (1,8), (1,1), (8,8), (8,1)}{
\node[piace] at \pos {\pos};
}
\foreach \pos in {(current), (target)}{
\node[piace] at \pos {\pos};
}
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```
This code snippet creates an 8x8 chessboard where white has just moved to the space indicated by the coordinates `(current)` and `(target)`. You can adjust the coordinates and placement of the pieces as needed to represent the desired FEN notation.

